VI  - 43
IP  - 1
DP  - 2023 Jan-Mar
TI  - [Pneumobilia, pneumoperitoneum and pneumowirsung of traumatic etiology: Case 
      report and review of the literature].
PG  - 60-64
AB  - Pneumobilia is a phenomenon associated with the presence of a biliary-enteric 
      fistula or manipulation of the bile duct during procedures or surgical 
      interventions that cause dysfunction of the sphincter of Oddi. A known, but 
      infrequently reported event, is the increase in intraabdominal pressure after 
      closed abdominal trauma, which causes pneumobilia due to a mechanism of 
      retrograde air leakage towards the bile duct. Depending on the general compromise 
      of each patient, the prognosis can vary from a benign condition that only 
      requires conservative management, to being life threatening. We present the case 
      of a 75-year-old male patient who, after suffering a closed thoraco-abdominal 
      trauma, presented with rib fracture and, in addition, gallbladder wall rupture, 
      pneumoperitoneum, pneumobilia, and pneumowirsung, having a favorable clinical 
      course after receiving conservative management.
