TI  - Nonoperative management of blunt traumatic cardiac rupture: considerations of a 
      novel approach.
PG  - 1341-3
LID - S0003-4975(12)00447-X [pii]
LID - 10.1016/j.athoracsur.2012.02.085 [doi]
AB  - Blunt traumatic cardiac rupture carries a dismal prognosis. Patients who survive 
      to presentation are treated with prompt surgical repair. Operative intervention 
      carries significant morbidity and mortality, as these patients present in 
      extremis. Intervention can be complicated by prior cardiac surgery. Obliteration 
      of the pericardial space from adhesions may offer the patient an alternative 
      conservative option under rare circumstances. We present a case of an older man 
      with blunt cardiac rupture caused by a motor vehicle crash. The patient remained 
      hemodynamically stable as his rupture only communicated with a small space within 
      his obliterated pericardial sac. He was managed nonoperatively.
