DP  - 2010 Mar
TI  - [High-age thoracic impalement injury treated by conservative therapy].
PG  - 184-7
AB  - Thoracic impalement injury is uncommon mechanism of injury. We describe a case 
      treated successfully by non-surgical management. An 87-year-old male got 
      impalement injury in his room by a part of stepladder on right anterior chest 
      wall. He was found to be alert and hemodynamically stable, so computed tomography 
      (CT) scan was performed. Chest CT showed right-sided hemopneumothorax and 
      pulmonary contusion, but no cardiac and great vessels injury. We discussed about 
      performing video-assisted thoracic surgery (VATS), but selected non-surgical 
      treatment including chest drainage at that time, because of low possibilities of 
      massive bleeding and apprehension of postoperative complication resulting from 
      patient's high age. He had uneventful recovery and was discharged on foot 13 days 
      after admission.
