IS  - 0022-5282 (Linking)
VI  - 29
IP  - 3
DP  - 1989 Mar
TI  - Occult diaphragmatic injury from stab wounds to the lower chest and abdomen.
PG  - 292-8
AB  - Ninety-five patients with stab wounds to the lower chest and abdomen underwent 
      routine abdominal exploration. Eighteen of these patients had diaphragmatic 
      injury and in five patients it was the only injury found. Isolated diaphragmatic 
      injury in asymptomatic patients cannot be reliably delineated by either serial 
      physical examination or peritoneal lavage. Delayed recognition of incarcerated 
      diaphragmatic hernia after stab wounds to the lower left chest and upper abdomen 
      has an associated mortality rate of 36%. The anatomic area of concern can be 
      defined as stab wounds that penetrate the left side of the chest below the fourth 
      intercostal space anteriorly, the sixth intercostal space laterally, and the tip 
      of the scapula posteriorly. Exploratory laparotomy is necessary in these patients 
      until a reliable nonoperative method is established that can exclude injuries to 
      the diaphragm.
